Iavan Pijoos, News24Three Metrorail train carriages were gutted by a fire at Nolungile Station in Site C, Khayelitsha, Cape Town, affecting train travel in the city. The cause of the fire is being investigated. (Lulama Zenzile, Die Burger) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town - Metrorail in Cape Town on Tuesday suspended trains in the central service corridor following a service delivery protest in Langa, the railway operator said in a statement.A train was torched between Bellville and Tygerberg Stations and the driver had to flee for his life.A large amount of equipment, including signals, was damaged during the protest over housing on Tuesday morning. It would take several days to be repaired.&nbsp;Burning obstacles were put on the railway lines and protesters threw stones at staff vehicles.All stations on the Khayelitsha and Kapteinsklip corridor would be closed on Wednesday morning, for the safety of both commuters and staff. No buses would be provided due to the large number of commuters who used this service.One person was arrested with a petrol bomb and 33 others were held for public violence.Regional manager Richard Walker said they would not risk operating trains to the area. He called on authorities to bring the protest, which was unrelated to the rail service, to an end protect lives and state assets.&nbsp;&nbsp;24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.